<Text>(Translated by Google) After going back and forth twice in Ridgecrest's main drag and not being inspired by any of the classic fast food restaurants (as it was late and the only American style diner we stopped at was closed) we settled on Pizza Hut, to take a break from hamburgers and the like.
As always, we took refuge in the comfort of the Cheese Pizza (which would later be the margherita), divided between us parents and the two children. Not bad pizza, considering we are in the middle of nowhere with stars and stripes.
Of course, if you don't arrive late like us, you don't risk finding the young boy cashier waiter passing the rag by your side while you are with pizza in your mouth.

(Original)
Dopo aver fatto avanti e dietro due volte nella via principale di Ridgecrest e non essere stati ispirati da nessuno dei fast food classici (visto che era tardi e l'unico diner stile americano in cui ci siamo fermati era chiuso) abbiamo optato per Pizza Hut, per fare una pausa da hamburger e affini.
Come sempre ci siamo rifugiati nel comfort della Cheese Pizza (che sarebbe poi la margherita), divisa tra noi genitori e i due bambini. Pizza non male, considerando che siamo nel bel mezzo del nulla a stelle strisce.
Certo, se poi non arrivate tardi come noi, non rischiate di trovarvi il giovane ragazzo cassiere cameriere che vi passa lo straccio a fianco mentre siete con la pizza in bocca.< /Text>< pictures>

<name>Rithwik Hari</name>< Date>
1572386530866<//Date>
<rating>5< /rating>< Review>
This is one of my favorite spots in SF.

The pizza is fantastic (admittedly the only thing I've ordered aside from cheesecake which was also great). Thin crust, fantastic toppings like house made sausage, wild mushrooms, and Humboldt Fog goat cheese.

The owner used to be in the beer/wine business and always has a fantastic rotating selection of draft beers.

But on top of the actual food and drink, the environment at Kezar is incredible. I used to live in the neighborhood and would be there multiple times a week; nowadays, I try make the trek to Cole Valley every week to catch up with all the other regulars who I have gotten to know (including the owner Basim, who is a wonderful guy). There are TVs to watch the game, and there's usually great conversation to be had there if you're looking for it too. I can't count the number of times I've wandered into Kezar alone and left beaming after an unexpectedly great chat.

They have a large space in the back for big groups! Sometimes this place gets randomly swamped with a party of like 20 in the back which can hold up service, but otherwise service is prompt and friendly; the staff are all really kind.

If I ever leave the city, this is a place that I will always associate with SF. It is a special place; it feels like there aren't many establishments like this in SF nowadays. Definitely worth a visit, maybe I'll see you there sometime!<//Review>

< text>
KP is one of my favorite spots in the city.

A great draught beer selection served just the way beer is supposed to be served. Local breweries are always well represented and I'm thrilled to often see Fieldwork on tap.

The food is pizza with quality ingredients, with some solid appetizer and salad options (go for arugula!). The happy hour pizza deal (2 toppings 8" I believe) with a $1 off pint is a great treat at the end of the day.

TVs show whatever game is one but it doesn't feel like a sports bar. A very unique ambiance (see giant saltwater fish tank!). The lounge in the back is great for larger groups.<//text>

< name>
C Squared</name>
<time>1580762230811< /time>< rate>
5</rate>
< text>
I love this place SO MUCH. The first time I came here, I actually thought it was a bar from the outside. When I walked in I realized my mistake, but opted to stay anyway because it looked like they had some beer on tap. I'm so glad I did. They not only have incredible craft beers on tap (especially some heavy and delicious stouts/porters for those dark beer fans), they have a HUMBOLDT FOG PIZZA. If that doesn't sell you on this place I don't know what will.
The ambience is sort of strange here, but in the most charming way. There's a massive aquarium in the middle of the room that divides the place in half, a great but small bar that serves wine and some of the best tasting beer I've had in the bay, there's almost always a gaggle of circus performers from the circus school next door hanging out in the back unwinding after their classes, and the bar plays the strangest selection of music‚Äîsometimes it's EDM, sometimes 90's garage rock, you just never know. Oh, and the best damn pizza on earth, that mean Humboldt Fog Pizza. Definitely check it out, it's such a great little undiscovered gem of the inner sunset/ashbury/cole valley area.<//text>
<pics>None</pics><resp>{'time': 1581014351624, 'text': "Nothing like enjoying a Humboldt Fog pizza and a pint of craft beer while gazing at our massive aquarium. You'll have to spread the word about our place. Thanks for the stars, and we'll see you soon. -Kezar Pizzetta Staff"}</resp>< Gmap_id>

<Rate>5<//Rate><review>Third time here and just have to get a quick rating up here as it's quickly becoming one of my favourite spots. The quality of food and ingredients is so high for what otherwise appears to be a quintessentially perfect neighborhood bar. There used to be more places like this in San Francisco that were comfortable, welcoming, unpretentious, somewhat quirky (e.g. fish tank), and second to none in quality.

I have a birthday coming up and can't think of any place I'd rather invite 20 friends meet at to eat, drink and laugh. There's a loungey area in the back that seems perfect for such a meet up...

Anyways, go there and help keep places like this open in SF.< /review><name>Jeremy Brooks<//name><Time>1555824701493<//Time></record></dataset><record>

< Text>
To my great amazement, all of the stuff I shipped from Boston to Berkeley with U-Pack arrived completely unscathed, exactly as I had packed it up, with zero damage... in exactly 10 days after the cube was picked up (1st pic is Boston, 2nd is Berkeley).

After reading reviews online of the various moving companies, it seemed like every option would lead to damaged, broken, or late items. However, U-Pack managed to ship everything perfectly safely. Plus, it was cheap ($1750), and easy. I enjoyed being able to pack the items myself to make sure they were secure. I have used professional movers before, and ended up with several broken and lost items.

The only downside is that if you don't have a driveway, you will have to contact your city to obtain a moving container permit for the street. This has to be done about a week or 10 days in advance, and can be a bit of a hassle. It also cost about $200 in each place.<//Text>

<review>You can order pick up and delivery by text. They did what they said they would do. Far cheaper than a POD ($1300) for the price and charged by the foot so if you have more items this is the way to go. There is no perfect system for a long distance move. There was some tiny water leakage in the trailer but no damage, get a tarp(s) if you're concerned. Also plan on spending $300 on tie downs and quality blankets by the bale from Harbor Freight. Be aware if you're doing an out of state move and they quote you 7 - 10 days that you better not schedule movers until the 10 days or the full time is up - you'll end up paying extra hotel fees, if you think the trailer will arrive early - don't, until they text you- not much to be said, you can try the dispatcher for a status. Do not even consider an early arrival for an interstate move, they add freight to the rest of the trailer.  PODs is no faster. Stay at a friend's house for the duration. Lastly, get a quality mover in your area to both pack and load and unload, don't even remotely consider doing this yourself. CA to TX - $4,100 and full 10 days time, + $1500 to pack and load, I provided most of my own boxes - get a quality TV box,  $500 to unload(sell your blankets at a discount to the destination mover, mine gave me 50% of the cost, thrown in the wardrobe boxes for free.) Total cost roughly $6,400 including blankets and everything. Considering I save about $34,000 a year in costs from one state to another, I consider it the cost of doing business like a home refi. Personally I don't think there's anything better out there than U-Pack, a dedicated move costs 3 times as much.< /review>< pics>

<UserId.>113046274447746775735<//UserId.><user_name>S. Kamment<//user_name>< Date>
1531844297017</Date>
<Rate>5< /Rate><Text>Never having moved an entire house of belongings before, I had no prior experience with moving companies. We were moving from Ohio to California, so it had to be done in one trip. I decided to go with a container cube, as it was more economical than the option of a moving truck. We gave away or disposed of a lot before packing, taking only the absolute minimum. A small cube holds a surprising amount of furniture and boxes. But order an extra cube at first just in case you need it, as there‚Äôs no charge to return one if it turns out you don‚Äôt. There were five main criteria I considered when I chose U-Pack: Price, cube type and size, how the cube would be delivered and fit on our property, pickup and return policy and user reviews. All but one were comparable to Pods. Both companies‚Äô small cube size and composition, level transport, delivery policies and good reviews were similar. However, U-Pack pricing was significantly lower, for us by over $1000 for one small cube! Also, due to the method Pods uses to deliver a cube, it would not have allowed us to keep it behind the house, where it would be out of sight of the street (be sure you check for space clearance before committing). I rejected U-Haul, mostly because their cubes seemed flimsy and possibly not waterproof, and Pack Rat, because of mixed user reviews and complaints about poor service. Users who complained across the board about their items ending up jostled and broken must not have packed their cubes securely enough, because our items arrived exactly as we packed them, like sardines in a can. Pack it as if the cube would be shaken like a can of paint in a paint store, and your stuff should be fine. The drivers at both ends of the trip were very polite and professional. They really knew how to operate a forklift to finesse the cube into precise position. The support staff was very easy to work with on the phone, helping me with all of the small details with patience and good humor. The Northern Ohio folks were easy to reach, and delivery and pickup of the cube was very prompt. The Oakland office didn‚Äôt answer their phone the several times I tried calling, so I had to get to them through the main office. We were scheduled for a delivery between 1 and 5 p.m. but didn‚Äôt get it until 7:30, which inconvenienced us. That would have been fine had they called us early on to tell us that they were so behind schedule. Also, they kept calling our old, disconnected phone number in Ohio, even though I gave them two cell numbers as well. So communication could have been much better in California, but otherwise service was excellent. I highly recommend this company for their ReloCubes.<//Text>< pics>
None< /pics>

<text>I cannot say enough good things about my experience with U-Pack!
EASY, trustworthy, affordable, no scams, kind customer service, delivered on time and everything was in the same condition as it was when I loaded the truck.

I had gone thru a broker company first, who sent me two shady moving companies that I turned away each time as they were trying to charge me WAY more then my signed contract with the broker. They also tried to demand I sign a blank Bill of Lading and neither could promise my delivery date (they legally have 30 days to deliver you your belongings). To make matters worse, they take your items off the truck, store them in a warehouse and then load them back onto another truck (which you dont get to witness) and only when they find other items to be sent to the state your moving to. Ill spare you the additional horrific details of each time they came to my house and the hours and days of communication I spent with the broker company over this, a complete nightmare! Luckily, I had time on my side and didn't feel pressured into signing with one of these moving companies that would ultimately cost me hundreds more then originally agreed upon. However, almost four weeks from the day I contracted the broker they still had not sent me a reputable moving company so I requested my deposit back, which is still an on-going issue.

A friend recommend U-Pack as she also had a great experience with them. Thank goodness she did, I wish I had called them first!
With that said, I did my due-diligence... I read the Bill of Lading and Tariff on-line prior to signing the contract, I packed my items thoroughly, and I hired two local moving guys to pack the truck properly and tie everything down with rope. The "security wall" was locked into place with my personal locks. The best part was I got to select the square footage I wanted based on the household list I filled out with U-Pack on-line. If I went over that sq ft I would be charged a very reasonable rate per square foot. If I went under the selected sq ft I received 100% of my money back. The broker only gives you back 10% of your money if you go under the square feet they recommend. You are in complete control of this and not the movers who are packing your items onto the truck and gain if you go over in sq ft. I was the one packing the truck with friends I knew exactly what my potential fee could be. However, I was exactly to the square foot I received from the on-line form. And U-Pack has no hidden weight fees like the other moving companies. The other movers weigh the truck hours away from your home so you cant validate an empty truck, load your household items and then say they weigh it right after, however, I found out the movers had another pick-up after mine and then were going to weigh the truck at a weigh station hours away from me so I was unable to validate it was just my items on the truck being weighed. You are charged the difference of weight, that left too many variables in that equation to get scammed. The U-Pack truck was picked-up the next day, I was able to track the truck during the move and they communicated with me consistently both at the trailer drop-off and the trailer delivery. All my furniture, paintings, decor and kitchen items arrived safely and undamaged 7 business days after the pick-up.

I will absolutely call U-Pack again for my next move! What you see is what you get, no hidden fees.<//text>< Pictures>

My experience was mostly good; every driver was professional and communicative, the representative who helped me initially set up everything over the phone was great, and the service center at the end of the trip was very easy to work with. The Concord center, however, was their own story.

The ReloCube dropoff happened on Thursday with no issues, although we learned that we would need someone there to help guide the driver out again upon pickup because someone on the ground would need to guide them past the electrical line running to the house once they'd lifted up the cube. I called and scheduled pickup for the next day and they said I was all set for a pickup sometime between 9-5. Because you just don't leave all of your belongings outside overnight in Oakland, I set up help to load everything up Friday morning before 9am so that the cubes would be ready whenever a driver came by. I called again around 10:30am to confirm that pickup would happen that day. They assured me that someone would come by to pick up the cubes, probably somewhere between 1-5pm because it was a busy day.

At 4:30pm, I called again just to check that the driver was still coming. At this point, I was informed that I wasn't on the schedule and would have to wait for the following Tuesday. It took several minutes on the phone with an extremely unhelpful representative whose tagline was "sorry, you're not on the schedule, I can't help you" before I convinced him to contact the drivers. He eventually got back on the line with me and said that either a driver would be out at my place around 8pm or would call to tell me that he couldn't make it.

At 10:30pm, still no driver, still no phone call. I call again and am told that the driver is still on his way. Pickup finally happened at midnight and was thankfully painless with getting past the electrical lines in the dark.

Again, the rest of the process was very smooth and painless, but something clearly isn't working right if I called three times to confirm pickup and was only told on the third attempt that I'd never been added to the schedule. And as for whoever was manning the phone at the Concord center at 4:30pm on August 31, 2018, that interaction was unacceptable for a service representative.</text>

< rating>
5<//rating>
<Review>Moved from Sebastopol, CA to Austin, TX. We are a couple moving what amounts to a studio/1 bedroom apartment worth of stuff - 1 queen bed, four seat dining room table, 5 small chairs, about 25 medium to large boxes, two bikes and a few other odds and ends. We reserved one cube and loaded it ourselves at the Oakland station. Everyone at the loading station was friendly and helpful. We rented a uHaul, drove to the Oakland loading station and were directed to our cube. They have a bunch of cubes at the end of and uncovered lot and you just back up and load it your self. I would not recommend doing this in the rain!

Having worked in shipping and receiving, I have seen many seemingly sturdy loads ship, only to be destroyed in transit. Keep in mind the cube will be loaded onto a truck with a forklift that will tilt the cube back at an angle. Everything inside will shift to some extent. Then it will transported in traffic, on poorly maintained U.S. roads, to its destination. Everything inside the cube with be dumped and jostled around, probably a lot.

Knowing this, we strapped our bed and table to the side walls and filled the whole bottom with our largest, sturdiest boxes. Then moved up with lighter/less full boxes. Then put our bikes and random stuff on top and tried to wrap loose items in moving blankets. (I would not recommend having any loose items, some of our stuff got scratched because it was not wrapped in anything protective at all) Make sure to bring a pad lock to lock up the cube.

We loaded our cube on a Monday and it arrived in Austin the following Monday and we unloaded it on Tuesday. The Austin uPack station was just like the one in Oakland. Went into the front office and they directed us to our cube, pulled the uHaul around and loaded it up.

We had almost nothing get damaged in transit, only some scratches on exposed furniture and  two broken glasses. It is very important to understand that they way the cube is loaded determines how well it handles the road, loading and offloading. If we do this again we will pack everything tighter and make sure we wrap everything a little better.

The total cost was $2002, plus the uhaul at both ends. That is that same as the price we were quoted even though we picked up a day after it arrived. Overall, this was a very pleasant experience that I would recommend to anyone doing a cross country move with a small amount of furniture.</Review><pics>None<//pics>< response>
None</response>

I thought I was being smart using U Pack on my cross country move from South Carolina to California. I didn't want to drive a uhaul for five days and 3k miles, and U Pack's pricing was fair. We loaded our entire house into a budget rental truck, and drove it to the ABF freight center where we then packed it into their trailer.

We packed meticulously. I invested over $200 in moving blankets, mattress covers, plastic wrapping for all of my furniture and new boxes. We spent three hours packing the UPACK / ABF trailer until it was perfect, doing everything we could to make sure our stuff would arrive in one piece. The ABF guys even helped us tie down our gear and close the door for us, saying everything looked good.

When we got to California and opened the door on our trailer, everything we owned was destroyed. I dont know what are you talking about !!, whatever you do its your word against mine !! ' OMG i was about to punch her but I DO HAVE MANNERS and EDUCATION !!! PLEASE DONT GO TO THIS STORE !!

The store manager Sally's Beauty Supply "ROSALINDA" offended my sister and rejected a gift card because she allegedly "can be stolen" and humiliated her in front of everyone in the store.
The store MANAGER will charge you for the products
Then he made him pay for the products, he made him sign the receipt
In the end he did not give the products that my sister bought with the "stolen card" (if it was stolen for me to use)

(Original)
Worst store ever!!!! The store manager of Sally's Beauty Supply "ROSALINDA" offended my sister and refused to accept a gift card because supposedly "it might be stolen" and humiliated her infront of everyone in the store.
She charged her for the products
Then didnt gave her a receipt and make her signed it
She refused to give her the products she just purchased with the " stolen gift card"(if it was stolen then why use it!???)
Then i went to make a report and she started yelling, admitting she humiliated my sister and said " what report are you gonna make? i dont know what are you talking about!!, whatever you do its your word against mine!!' OMG i was about to punch her but I DO HAVE MANNERS and EDUCATION!!!  PLEASE DONT GO TO THIS STORE!!

La manager de la tienda Sally's Beauty Supply "ROSALINDA" ofendio a mi hermana y le rechazo una targeta de regalo porque supuestamente "puede ser robada" y la humillo enfrente de todos en la tienda.
La MANAGER de la tienda le cobro por los productos
Luego le hizo pagar por los productos, le hizo firmar el recivo
Al final no le dio los productos que mi hermana compro con la "targeta robada" ( si fue robada para que la utilizo)
Despues de que me entere fui a reclamarme  y hacer un reporte, ROSALINDA me empezo a gritonear, admitiendo que ella abia humillado a mi hermana y me dijo" que reporte quieres hacer? no se de que estas ablando!!, Lo que sea  que vas acer es tu palabra contra la mia!!!" dios mio estaba apunto de golpearla pero YO SI TENGO modeales eh educacion!! PORFAVOR NO BAYAN A ESTA TIENDA!!< /review>

<date>1561474677888<//date><Text>One of my most favorite things to do when I travel is to do a guided waking tour. It changes your entire experience of a city when you learn a bit of it's history. We did the SF in one day, five-hour tour, learning about the Gold Rush-era buildings, Nob Hill mansions and palaces, the history of Chinatown, North Beach/Little Italy, the biggest cathedral in the city, and the modern day downtown skyscrapers. We also took an obligatory cable car ride and learned how those came to be! My most favorite part of travel is taking back with me a little bit of the history. Thank you to our very wonderful and funny your guide Britt for taking us on such an adventure!

People, do what the company recommends and dress in layers and wear comfortable walking shoes. Afterall, it is San Francisco and there will always be funny weather and a bit of hill climbing. Was sad to see folks on my tour struggle on a five hour with heels/wedges.<//Text>< Name>

< text>
My flight didn't leave until the evening so I had a day to kill in San Francisco solo. I signed up for a 3 hour tour that began at 10am not really expecting much, but boy was I impressed! Britt took a small group of us around North Beach, Chinatown, to Lombard Street and the Fisherman's Wharf - and not to the touristy part, but to the working side of it, which was really cool. <rate>5<//rate><review>I went on the all in one 5 hour walking tour when I was in San Francisco earlier this month. It sounds like a lot, but you also cover a lot of ground over the course of the tour. My tour guide was Britt, and he was informative and enthusiastic about sharing information about San Francisco. I was a little worried about lunch, not being familiar with the area and lunch stop happening in Chinatown. But Britt provided each of us with a card with his recommendations (definitely take him up on that! best Dim Sum I've ever had!). The tour starts with early San Fran history with the gold rush, then it expanded to Nob Hill, Chinatown, and Little Italy. I really can't recommend this enough. And it's cost is to cover the cable car--anything else you pay is a price you decide.</review>< Pictures>

<GmapID>0x8085809c3f111f27:0xd19391d64ff103e5< /GmapID><Pics>None<//Pics>< text>
We stayed in San Francisco for three days-it was our first time in the city so we didn't know much about the city. Boy, is there a lot of walking in SF! Our tour guide knew a lot about the area, the history, the stories, and even the little tidbits about buildings that you would never think to look at.

This is a 'pay what you like' tour which meant it was way cheaper than the $30-40 per person tours offered elsewhere. I thought it was cool that the guide carried a credit card reader because it's always so difficult to keep cash in new cities.

If you are going to come to San Francisco for a visit, you have to try Free Tours by Foot!< /text>

< Review>
Britt was an awesome walking tour guide. He made the walk easy, no big hills! For those of us coming from places like Florida that are very flat and walking many days in SF, this was a nice break to the uphill climbs we did all week! lol I was on the Secrets, Scandals and Scoundrels tour and it was so interesting and funny. Britt is a great story teller and takes you to relevant places in the city and gives you a little of the humorous background on some of the characters that helped build SF. My personal favorite is the story about the Emperor of the United States. This is one I am going to work into my classroom simply because it is too humorous to leave out of a conversation of our past leaders. I highly recommend this tour, or any of Britt's tours as I am sure they are all entertaining.< /Review>

<rate>5< /rate>< text>
One of the best tours ever....don't be fooled by seeing 'free tours by foot'. You cannot get a similar experience even if you pay for a private tour guide. Britt is so passionate about SF - the city he loves to be in and the stories he presents is nothing less than commendable. Great job out there keeping the SF history alive - we have been to Secrets, Scandals and Scoundrels of San Francisco and it was like taking you back to the past for 3 hours. It's a good 1-1.5 mile walk but you will not feel the distance at all. Britt has loads of information that you cannot get even in 'google' unless you research for multiple days. Feel free to ask any number of Qs you have and Britt will make sure he answers every Q or points you to one if he isnt 100% sure. The best tour guide ever - YOU ROCK!!</text>

< name>
Nick Lukefahr< /name>
< Text>
Wasn't sure what to expect here as my coworkers seemed to think it was just so-so compared to their other normal choices in the area.

The atmosphere was good. It was a quiet Monday evening. I ordered the Wedge Salad and the Ultimate Mixed Grill (stuffed shrimp, grilled shrimp, scallops, salmon). Both were items were very tasty! Got the wedge with some extra bleu cheese crumbles (which makes it better automatically) The scallops were very well cooked, though could have used some kind of light sauce. The salmon was a little dry, but not too bad. Prices overall weren't bad for the area, I've seen worse.

The only thing that disappointed me slightly was the limited number of times we saw our waitress during the meal. Probably 4 times total not including ordering, food delivery, and checks, and the place was empty. She was very friendly, however. Oh, and they didn't have Dr. Pepper, my favorite soft drink. :'(

Will come back. Would recommend to a friend.<//Text>

<text>Made a reservation for Thanksgiving dinner for 6 PM for a party of 4. They were busy, and after a 15 minute wait, we decided to sit at an empty table in the bar. Not a problem, we liked being around the TV's and the action.
Waitress was good, attentive to our needs. Food was mediocre at best. Last year at Thanksgiving I was in Bozeman MT and went to Ted Turners Montana Grill for Thanksgiving. Had a great meal with turkey and all the fixings, including desert, for $25. The meal at McCormick was $27.5. The beans were good and warm, the rest of the meal felt like I was eating in a high school cafeteria. The scoops of stuffing and mashed potatoes were institutional at best. The stuffing for the 2 of us that ate the turkey was cold, and when we told the waitress she promptly brought us hot stuffing, although it was still dry and tasteless. The cranberry was OK, too bad after two teaspoons the tiny amount they gave us was gone. My friend asked for more and got some from the waitress. The turkey was similar to the kind your purchase at the supermarket when they take out a turkey and slice it, not the thick and meaty pieces I am used to for Thanksgiving, and certainly not as good as my meal at the Montana Grill. And to top it off, desert was not included. < Text>
3.5, they really need more stars or move to a 1 - 10 ranking.  I'd give it a 7 out of 10.  Bagels are pretty good, I'm from NYC.  The coffee was fine, and I've gone to Noah's for over a decade, most visits in Westwood.   The negatives to this place is the length of time to get through the line.  Sometimes I get a wedge of cream cheese and other times I get a thin coating, nit picking there.

A better rating is 7 out of 10.  The place has good bagels, fresh out of the oven and they are really really good.</Text>

This place has a great atmosphere, friendly service, and great views if you're in the dining section. My husband went to watch the NBA final game last night, and had a great time. Definitely recommend, but maybe try a seafood dish, which I'm sure will be better than the nachos, spinach- artichoke dip, and calamari. <Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPcVkwmJ7um6TrSTc3rRpauTstFEYVIl0xibIte=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOAd-RtzxKKkP-7AaDjPcJbjAbSjB2r29jIJGuB=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics><Rate>4<//Rate>< review>
This place has a great atmosphere, friendly service, and great views if you're in the dining section. My husband went to watch the NBA final game last night, and had a great time. We sat in the bar area, which was buzzing with excited sports fans. We ate during happy hour, and while the appetizers were only $7.95, the food was a bit bland, but we didn't have any entrees, so I couldn't speak for any signature dishes. Overall, it was enjoyable and my husband and son mentioned a few more times today, how much they enjoyed the crowd and staff at Tony P's. Definitely recommend, but maybe try a seafood dish, which I'm sure will be better than the nachos, spinach- artichoke dip, and calamari. The quesadilla was decent and so were the potato skins.</review>

< Text>
Gave it four stars because the server was not all that good. He came pretty quickly once we sat down but we got our food and asked for some hot sauce and it literally took him about 15-20 min to come back with it. We had finished our drinks and half our plates by the time he got back. This was on a slow night.

That aside, he was still a pretty nice guy and the food was incredible! We ordered the Spicy Louisiana plate and the Tilapia with baked potato. Both plates were exceptional. Prices were about average, Maybe even fair in comparison to what you might expect in Marina Del Rey.

Overall, I say at least give this place a try.
P.S. ~ lots of beer and drinks on hand!</Text>

104987181351027366602< /UserId.>
<name>Levon Juni</name><time>1578886995469</time><Rating>4</Rating>< text>
We were staying right next to Tony Ps on the Marina. We wanted a good salad (had dinner plans at an all you can eat Brazilian restaurant so wanted something lighter) and saw that this place had some good ratings. It was very busy, apparently the bar is popular for sports games. I ordered a cup of clam chowder and a southern fried chicken salad. I'm a fan of clam chowder, and only order from places that are on the water üôÇ. The chowder was good, but the salad was one of the best salads I've had. Good dressing, chicken was cooked well, had candied pecans, corn and some other stuff in it. Lots of flavor, very good. Service was a little slow, but it was busy.</text>

<rate>4</rate>< review>
An institution in Marina del Rey. Nice outdoor eating space. The menu is pretty typical - steaks, fish, salads, pizza. There is an extensive selection of beers. Service is generally good. Almost everything is garlicky, even when a "no garlic" request is made. The fish is often frozen - ask if you want something fresh and local. (Salmon is farmed, not wild, and comes from either the Pacific Northwest or the Atlantic.) The food is fine, but not spectacular. We eat here often because Grandma loves it, and she can get her bourbon. I like the bouillabaisse and the quinoa and beet salad.<//review>

<rate>2</rate><text>The food is mediocre at best- they definitely are relying on their great view of the marina to get people to come in, because it isn‚Äôt the food.
I ordered the fish and chips and added a wedge salad for $4.75. The wedge salad was just lettuce, tomato, and watery blue cheese. When I asked about the onions and the bacon the server said that isn‚Äôt available on the add-on wedge, only the appetizer wedge ($10.95). Nowhere on the menu does it call that out. The flavor really comes from those components mixing with the others. I would recommend skipping the add-on wedge- it was flavorless. It didn‚Äôt even have blue cheese crumbles to help boost the flavor.
Two people at my table ordered the French Onion Soup and they described it as ‚Äúunderwhelming.‚Äù
The fish and chips were decent- not a ton of flavor but tasted fresh, the breading was a little doughy. I substituted the fries for veggies- the veggies were good and you get a large portion (I bet if they scaled down their veggie portion slightly they‚Äôd be able to afford to put some onions and bacon on the wedge salad :) )
Someone at my table had the mahi-mahi and really enjoyed it.
Another person in my party had the salmon- it was cooked nicely but again did not have a lot of flavor.
Our server at the end of the meal explained that an 18% gratuity was added on because ‚ÄúI have to split the tips with my co-workers.‚Äù That really left a bad taste in our mouths because when I said ‚Äúyou have to split it from this table?‚Äù He said ‚Äúyeah we have to tip out.‚Äù I worked as a server through high school and college- tipping out is par for the course. At every restaurant I‚Äôve worked for there is some form of tipping out your back of house, bar, hostess, bussers, etc. It wasn‚Äôt because we were a large group so he had to split the tips with his co-workers, it‚Äôs because that is what you do as a server since they are the ones helping you satisfy your customers.
Two of the people in our party own a boat in the marina and were looking for another restaurant to frequent nearby, but based on last night‚Äôs experience will not be returning to Tony P‚Äôs.< /text>< Pics>
None< /Pics>
< Resp>
{'time': 1555364328305, 'text': 'HI Amy, thanks for coming into Tony P\'s. I am sorry about the confusion on the wedge salad. We do offer 2 different wedge salads. One is an add on to an entree (Iceburg wedge, tomatoes, red onions and dressing. $4.75) and one is on the entree salad section (Iceburg wedge, tomatoes, red onions, smoked bacon, crumbled blue cheese and dressing $10.95). We will retrain the salad cook who needs to stir the blue cheese dressing that we make in house, that is full of chunks of blue cheese. I apologize that you didn\'t get that. Regarding the 18% gratuity which is added on to parties of 6 or more. The server didn\'t do a very good job of explaining it to you. Like most restaurants, we add gratuity to tables of 6 or more people. Since you were a server before you understand this policy. Please e-mail me your server\'s name (tony@tonyps.com) and what time you came in. If you do not agree with the added gratuity, please let the manager know and we would take it off.  Our servers "tip out" to the Bussers, Food Runners and Bartenders that help them service your table. They do not share their tips with any other servers. All of this should not have anything to do with you getting great service when you come in. It is all house keeping issues on our side of the restaurant business and I am sorry if you were inconvenienced. Anytime you come into Tony P\'s, and you are not satisfied with service or food please let our managers know. We want everyone to have a great experience.'}< /Resp>

<UserId.>104255834287005683761<//UserId.><user_name>Rob Savory</user_name><date>1547477446607</date>< rating>
5< /rating>
< Text>
I've come here many times and always have a great time. The outdoor seating is ideal for datenight as there is a view of the marina (there are heat lamps) and all the boats and the marina are lit up. Great to watch the sunset. It is a beautiful ambiance for either a table for two or the whole family.
There is also a bar with lots of beers on tap and the bartenders make great cocktails too! This place is set up with tons of TVs so that every football game is available to watch during the season, or any sport for that matter. I think I come here for every big sport event; football playoffs, basketball plays, Sunday football brunch, and baseball playoffs.
The food is great. I love getting the cajun penne pasta; great portion size for your money and tastes amazing. The fish and chips are the best I think I've ever had and there is a tuxedo cake desert which is a must every time I go here.
The wait staff is very friendly and I don't think I have ever sat long for any help or service. They are attentive and approachable. I highly recommend this place to anyone who lives in the area (or doesn't) or someone visiting and staying near LAX. Won't be disappointed.< /Text>

< review>
I've been here several times, and up until last night have gotten decent food and drinks. Last night was awful. The service was so slow - 2 hours for dinner for six people (and the restaurant was not crowded). The cider they brought me was in a bottle that looked like it came from the back of the fridge and had been sitting in there for months - the label was ripped and worn, and the cider tasted like sesame seeds. I got a replacement at no charge, but they really shouldn't have served it at all, it was clearly expired. They served my friend's salad in a bowl that had a huge crack down the side. The waiter declined to take our food order after we told him what appetizer we wanted, even though we were all ready, then took 20 minutes to come back. They got two orders wrong (sides were wrong). It was all around extremely disappointing, I'm not sure I'll ever go back. On top of it, I had digestive distress afterwards, which might have been caused by old crab meat. It's too bad, they have a nice selection of beers on tap.</review>

<date>1529972693946<//date><rating>5</rating>< Review>
I have been coming here for over 15 years! Almost everytime I've been here, the staff is friendly and informed of their menu and selections. Timing to me is important in a restaurant, you don't like to be pushed through and out the door, and this establishment has never done that, actually the opposite there have been several times a group and myself come here and seriously feel like we at grandmas house, relaxing and down to earth environment. Big plus is they have amazing bloody Mary's and they keep a great stock beers (allagash my fav) the food menu is tried and true and they stick to what they're good at. Very refreshing to have this local gem for a good night out to eat. Overall my fav is the surf and turf crab/ or lobster and steak.< /Review>

<rating>5< /rating>< Review>
(Translated by Google) It is a cheap and delicious grill shop.
When I was walking along the yacht harbor, I found a shop full of many customers in the evening, so I entered.

Nearby are luxury resort apartments.

Salmon salad, pasta, and steak are just the right volume for a Japanese person to eat with four people.

All are delicious and reasonable.

After entering the store and opening the right door, there was a huge BAR space.

The store owner donated to various places, and a lot of letters of appreciation were displayed at the entrance.
